{
  "enabled": true,
  "name": "Generate Tests from Codebase",
  "description": "Scans the app's source code (Compose, SwiftUI, XML layouts), identifies screens, interactive elements, and user flows, then generates reusable YAML test scripts in e2e-tests/ folder with cross-platform support.",
  "version": "2",
  "when": {
    "type": "userTriggered"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "Scan the mobile app source code in this workspace. Find all UI source files — look for: Kotlin Compose (*.kt with @Composable), SwiftUI (*.swift with View protocol/body), XML layouts (res/layout/*.xml), UIKit storyboards/xibs. Also scan AndroidManifest.xml, navigation graphs, build.gradle for app metadata. STEP 0 — CHECK EXISTING CONTEXT: If prompt/ folder already exists, read ALL .md files in it FIRST. Use this existing context (credentials, flow order, known issues) as the foundation. When generating new prompt files in Step 2, MERGE with existing info — do not blindly overwrite user-provided context. If a file already has user-written content, preserve it and only add/update what's new from codebase scan. STEP 1 — DEEP SCAN & UNDERSTAND: Read through the ENTIRE codebase first. Identify all screens, activities, fragments, navigation flows, interactive elements, API calls, authentication logic, data models, custom views, and third-party SDKs. Understand the full app architecture BEFORE generating anything. STEP 2 — AUTO-GENERATE prompt/ FILES: Based on what you found, create the prompt/ folder and generate these files in order: a) prompt/00-prerequisites.md — App package name, main activity, login credentials needed (infer from auth logic), emulator setup notes (permissions to grant, settings to configure), test account info. b) prompt/01-testable-flows.md — List ALL flows that CAN be fully automated via UI automation. Group by module. Include recommended execution order based on dependencies (e.g., login first). For each flow: name, screens involved, why it's testable. c) prompt/02-untestable-flows.md — List ONLY the SPECIFIC STEPS within flows that are TRULY impossible to automate. CRITICAL RULES: 1) NEVER classify an entire flow as untestable. Break every flow into individual steps. Test ALL steps up to the point where automation truly cannot proceed. Only mark the SPECIFIC STEP as the untestable boundary, not the whole flow. 2) THIS IS A DEV/TEST ENVIRONMENT. There is NOTHING to worry about. Creating accounts, changing passwords, deleting data, making bookings — ALL ALLOWED. It's a test environment, not production. Do not be conservative. 3) The ONLY valid reasons a STEP is untestable: requires OTP/verification code from external email that cannot be accessed programmatically, requires interaction inside a third-party WebView whose elements cannot be inspected, requires physical hardware input (camera capture, fingerprint scan), requires real money payment processing. 4) THESE ARE EXPLICITLY ALLOWED (never use as reason to skip): creating real accounts (it's dev environment — create freely), changing passwords (use throwaway account), deleting accounts (it's test data), creating bookings/tickets (allowed), modifying server data (allowed), file uploads (try adb push). 5) Example of CORRECT classification: Sign Up flow has 10 steps. Steps 1-8 (form fill, validation, submit) = ALL TESTABLE. Step 9 (email verification OTP) = untestable boundary. So generate tests for steps 1-8, and only mark step 9 as untestable. 6) Example of WRONG classification: 'Sign Up — untestable because creates real accounts' → THIS IS WRONG. Test the entire form flow, submit it, create the account. It's dev environment. d) prompt/03-navigation-guide.md — How to navigate the app: entry points, screen transitions, tab structure, drawer/menu patterns, deep links if any. Common navigation patterns the agent should follow (e.g., 'always login first before testing authenticated screens'). e) prompt/04-known-issues.md — Workarounds for automation challenges found in code: custom views (MaterialCardView buttons → use coordinate tap), WebViews (can't inspect elements), animations (need waits), EditText that don't respond to ADB (use mobile_type_keys instead), any accessibility label gaps. STEP 3 — READ ALL prompt/*.md back as context for test script generation. STEP 4 — GENERATE TEST SCRIPTS: Only generate scripts for flows listed in prompt/01-testable-flows.md (up to their untestable boundary from prompt/02). Organize by MODULE — each module gets its own subfolder in e2e-tests/. For each module: generate COMPREHENSIVE tests as a strict QA engineer would: a) Happy path — all normal user flows with valid data, b) Negative path — invalid input, empty fields, wrong format, unauthorized access, c) Boundary values — max length, min length, special characters, emoji, zero values, d) Edge cases — state transitions, repeated actions, interruptions, back navigation mid-flow, e) Error handling — what happens when things go wrong. Be THOROUGH within each module. Think like a QA who wants to break things. Each test must have detailed steps and SPECIFIC expected results. Save YAML in e2e-tests/{module-name}/ (e.g., e2e-tests/sign-in/, e2e-tests/booking/). Include a module-order.yaml at e2e-tests/ root listing modules in dependency order. STEP 5 — METADATA: Generate e2e-tests/coverage.yaml listing elements and coverage. Read e2e-tests/version.yaml — increment or set to 1. Output summary: screens found, prompt files generated, testable vs untestable flows count, test scripts generated."
  }
}
